{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":1000,"text":"I want to start my story in Germany, in 1877,"},{"time":4000,"text":"with a mathematician named Georg Cantor."},{"time":6000,"text":"And Cantor decided he was going to take a line and erase the middle third of the line,"},{"time":11000,"text":"and then take those two resulting lines and bring them back into the same process, a recursive process."},{"time":16000,"text":"So he starts out with one line, and then two,"},{"time":18000,"text":"and then four, and then 16, and so on."},{"time":21000,"text":"And if he does this an infinite number of times, which you can do in mathematics,"},{"time":24000,"text":"he ends up with an infinite number of lines,"},{"time":26000,"text":"each of which has an infinite number of points in it."},{"time":29000,"text":"So he realized he had a set whose number of elements was larger than infinity."},{"time":33000,"text":"And this blew his mind. Literally. He checked into a sanitarium. (Laughter)"},{"time":36000,"text":"And when he came out of the sanitarium,"},{"time":38000,"text":"he was convinced that he had been put on earth to found transfinite set theory"},{"time":44000,"text":"because the largest set of infinity would be God Himself."},{"time":47000,"text":"He was a very religious man."},{"time":48000,"text":"He was a mathematician on a mission."}]},{"cues":[{"time":50000,"text":"And other mathematicians did the same sort of thing."},{"time":52000,"text":"A Swedish mathematician, von Koch,"},{"time":54000,"text":"decided that instead of subtracting lines, he would add them."},{"time":58000,"text":"And so he came up with this beautiful curve."},{"time":60000,"text":"And there's no particular reason why we have to start with this seed shape;"},{"time":63000,"text":"we can use any seed shape we like."},{"time":67000,"text":"And I'll rearrange this and I'll stick this somewhere -- down there, OK --"},{"time":71000,"text":"and now upon iteration, that seed shape sort of unfolds into a very different looking structure."},{"time":78000,"text":"So these all have the property of self-similarity:"},{"time":80000,"text":"the part looks like the whole."},{"time":82000,"text":"It's the same pattern at many different scales."}]},{"cues":[{"time":85000,"text":"Now, mathematicians thought this was very strange"},{"time":87000,"text":"because as you shrink a ruler down, you measure a longer and longer length."},{"time":92000,"text":"And since they went through the iterations an infinite number of times,"},{"time":94000,"text":"as the ruler shrinks down to infinity, the length goes to infinity."},{"time":100000,"text":"This made no sense at all,"},{"time":101000,"text":"so they consigned these curves to the back of the math books."},{"time":104000,"text":"They said these are pathological curves, and we don't have to discuss them."},{"time":108000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":109000,"text":"And that worked for a hundred years."}]},{"cues":[{"time":112000,"text":"And then in 1977, Benoit Mandelbrot, a French mathematician,"},{"time":117000,"text":"realized that if you do computer graphics and used these shapes he called fractals,"},{"time":122000,"text":"you get the shapes of nature."},{"time":124000,"text":"You get the human lungs, you get acacia trees, you get ferns,"},{"time":128000,"text":"you get these beautiful natural forms."},{"time":130000,"text":"If you take your thumb and your index finger and look right where they meet --"},{"time":134000,"text":"go ahead and do that now --"},{"time":136000,"text":"-- and relax your hand, you'll see a crinkle,"},{"time":139000,"text":"and then a wrinkle within the crinkle, and a crinkle within the wrinkle. Right?"},{"time":142000,"text":"Your body is covered with fractals."},{"time":144000,"text":"The mathematicians who were saying these were pathologically useless shapes?"},{"time":147000,"text":"They were breathing those words with fractal lungs."},{"time":149000,"text":"It's very ironic. And I'll show you a little natural recursion here."},{"time":153000,"text":"Again, we just take these lines and recursively replace them with the whole shape."},{"time":158000,"text":"So here's the second iteration, and the third, fourth and so on."}]},{"cues":[{"time":163000,"text":"So nature has this self-similar structure."},{"time":165000,"text":"Nature uses self-organizing systems."},{"time":167000,"text":"Now in the 1980s, I happened to notice"},{"time":170000,"text":"that if you look at an aerial photograph of an African village, you see fractals."},{"time":174000,"text":"And I thought, \"This is fabulous! I wonder why?\""},{"time":178000,"text":"And of course I had to go to Africa and ask folks why."},{"time":180000,"text":"So I got a Fulbright scholarship to just travel around Africa for a year"},{"time":186000,"text":"asking people why they were building fractals,"},{"time":188000,"text":"which is a great job if you can get it."},{"time":190000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":191000,"text":"And so I finally got to this city, and I'd done a little fractal model for the city"},{"time":198000,"text":"just to see how it would sort of unfold --"},{"time":201000,"text":"but when I got there, I got to the palace of the chief,"},{"time":204000,"text":"and my French is not very good; I said something like,"},{"time":207000,"text":"\"I am a mathematician and I would like to stand on your roof.\""},{"time":210000,"text":"But he was really cool about it, and he took me up there,"},{"time":213000,"text":"and we talked about fractals."},{"time":214000,"text":"And he said, \"Oh yeah, yeah! We knew about a rectangle within a rectangle,"},{"time":217000,"text":"we know all about that.\""},{"time":219000,"text":"And it turns out the royal insignia has a rectangle within a rectangle within a rectangle,"},{"time":223000,"text":"and the path through that palace is actually this spiral here."},{"time":227000,"text":"And as you go through the path, you have to get more and more polite."},{"time":231000,"text":"So they're mapping the social scaling onto the geometric scaling;"},{"time":234000,"text":"it's a conscious pattern. It is not unconscious like a termite mound fractal."}]},{"cues":[{"time":239000,"text":"This is a village in southern Zambia."},{"time":241000,"text":"The Ba-ila built this village about 400 meters in diameter."},{"time":245000,"text":"You have a huge ring."},{"time":247000,"text":"The rings that represent the family enclosures get larger and larger as you go towards the back,"},{"time":254000,"text":"and then you have the chief's ring here towards the back"},{"time":258000,"text":"and then the chief's immediate family in that ring."},{"time":261000,"text":"So here's a little fractal model for it."},{"time":262000,"text":"Here's one house with the sacred altar,"},{"time":265000,"text":"here's the house of houses, the family enclosure,"},{"time":268000,"text":"with the humans here where the sacred altar would be,"},{"time":271000,"text":"and then here's the village as a whole --"},{"time":273000,"text":"a ring of ring of rings with the chief's extended family here, the chief's immediate family here,"},{"time":278000,"text":"and here there's a tiny village only this big."},{"time":281000,"text":"Now you might wonder, how can people fit in a tiny village only this big?"},{"time":285000,"text":"That's because they're spirit people. It's the ancestors."},{"time":288000,"text":"And of course the spirit people have a little miniature village in their village, right?"},{"time":293000,"text":"So it's just like Georg Cantor said, the recursion continues forever."}]},{"cues":[{"time":296000,"text":"This is in the Mandara mountains, near the Nigerian border in Cameroon, Mokoulek."},{"time":300000,"text":"I saw this diagram drawn by a French architect,"},{"time":303000,"text":"and I thought, \"Wow! What a beautiful fractal!\""},{"time":305000,"text":"So I tried to come up with a seed shape, which, upon iteration, would unfold into this thing."},{"time":311000,"text":"I came up with this structure here."},{"time":313000,"text":"Let's see, first iteration, second, third, fourth."},{"time":317000,"text":"Now, after I did the simulation,"},{"time":319000,"text":"I realized the whole village kind of spirals around, just like this,"},{"time":322000,"text":"and here's that replicating line -- a self-replicating line that unfolds into the fractal."},{"time":328000,"text":"Well, I noticed that line is about where the only square building in the village is at."},{"time":333000,"text":"So, when I got to the village,"},{"time":335000,"text":"I said, \"Can you take me to the square building?"},{"time":337000,"text":"I think something's going on there.\""},{"time":339000,"text":"And they said, \"Well, we can take you there, but you can't go inside"},{"time":342000,"text":"because that's the sacred altar, where we do sacrifices every year"},{"time":345000,"text":"to keep up those annual cycles of fertility for the fields.\""},{"time":348000,"text":"And I started to realize that the cycles of fertility"},{"time":350000,"text":"were just like the recursive cycles in the geometric algorithm that builds this."},{"time":354000,"text":"And the recursion in some of these villages continues down into very tiny scales."}]},{"cues":[{"time":358000,"text":"So here's a Nankani village in Mali."},{"time":360000,"text":"And you can see, you go inside the family enclosure --"},{"time":363000,"text":"you go inside and here's pots in the fireplace, stacked recursively."},{"time":367000,"text":"Here's calabashes that Issa was just showing us,"},{"time":371000,"text":"and they're stacked recursively."},{"time":373000,"text":"Now, the tiniest calabash in here keeps the woman's soul."},{"time":375000,"text":"And when she dies, they have a ceremony"},{"time":377000,"text":"where they break this stack called the zalanga and her soul goes off to eternity."},{"time":382000,"text":"Once again, infinity is important."}]},{"cues":[{"time":386000,"text":"Now, you might ask yourself three questions at this point."},{"time":390000,"text":"Aren't these scaling patterns just universal to all indigenous architecture?"},{"time":394000,"text":"And that was actually my original hypothesis."},{"time":396000,"text":"When I first saw those African fractals,"},{"time":398000,"text":"I thought, \"Wow, so any indigenous group that doesn't have a state society,"},{"time":402000,"text":"that sort of hierarchy, must have a kind of bottom-up architecture.\""},{"time":405000,"text":"But that turns out not to be true."}]},{"cues":[{"time":407000,"text":"I started collecting aerial photographs of Native American and South Pacific architecture;"},{"time":411000,"text":"only the African ones were fractal."},{"time":413000,"text":"And if you think about it, all these different societies have different geometric design themes that they use."},{"time":419000,"text":"So Native Americans use a combination of circular symmetry and fourfold symmetry."},{"time":425000,"text":"You can see on the pottery and the baskets."},{"time":427000,"text":"Here's an aerial photograph of one of the Anasazi ruins;"},{"time":430000,"text":"you can see it's circular at the largest scale, but it's rectangular at the smaller scale, right?"},{"time":435000,"text":"It is not the same pattern at two different scales."}]},{"cues":[{"time":439000,"text":"Second, you might ask,"},{"time":440000,"text":"\"Well, Dr. Eglash, aren't you ignoring the diversity of African cultures?\""},{"time":444000,"text":"And three times, the answer is no."},{"time":446000,"text":"First of all, I agree with Mudimbe's wonderful book, \"The Invention of Africa,\""},{"time":450000,"text":"that Africa is an artificial invention of first colonialism,"},{"time":453000,"text":"and then oppositional movements."},{"time":455000,"text":"No, because a widely shared design practice doesn't necessarily give you a unity of culture --"},{"time":460000,"text":"and it definitely is not \"in the DNA.\""},{"time":463000,"text":"And finally, the fractals have self-similarity --"},{"time":465000,"text":"so they're similar to themselves, but they're not necessarily similar to each other --"},{"time":469000,"text":"you see very different uses for fractals."},{"time":471000,"text":"It's a shared technology in Africa."}]},{"cues":[{"time":474000,"text":"And finally, well, isn't this just intuition?"},{"time":477000,"text":"It's not really mathematical knowledge."},{"time":479000,"text":"Africans can't possibly really be using fractal geometry, right?"},{"time":482000,"text":"It wasn't invented until the 1970s."},{"time":485000,"text":"Well, it's true that some African fractals are, as far as I'm concerned, just pure intuition."},{"time":490000,"text":"So some of these things, I'd wander around the streets of Dakar"},{"time":493000,"text":"asking people, \"What's the algorithm? What's the rule for making this?\""},{"time":496000,"text":"and they'd say,"},{"time":497000,"text":"\"Well, we just make it that way because it looks pretty, stupid.\" (Laughter)"},{"time":500000,"text":"But sometimes, that's not the case."},{"time":503000,"text":"In some cases, there would actually be algorithms, and very sophisticated algorithms."},{"time":508000,"text":"So in Manghetu sculpture, you'd see this recursive geometry."},{"time":511000,"text":"In Ethiopian crosses, you see this wonderful unfolding of the shape."}]},{"cues":[{"time":516000,"text":"In Angola, the Chokwe people draw lines in the sand,"},{"time":520000,"text":"and it's what the German mathematician Euler called a graph;"},{"time":523000,"text":"we now call it an Eulerian path --"},{"time":525000,"text":"you can never lift your stylus from the surface"},{"time":527000,"text":"and you can never go over the same line twice."},{"time":530000,"text":"But they do it recursively, and they do it with an age-grade system,"},{"time":533000,"text":"so the little kids learn this one, and then the older kids learn this one,"},{"time":536000,"text":"then the next age-grade initiation, you learn this one."},{"time":539000,"text":"And with each iteration of that algorithm,"},{"time":542000,"text":"you learn the iterations of the myth."},{"time":544000,"text":"You learn the next level of knowledge."}]},{"cues":[{"time":547000,"text":"And finally, all over Africa, you see this board game."},{"time":549000,"text":"It's called Owari in Ghana, where I studied it;"},{"time":552000,"text":"it's called Mancala here on the East Coast, Bao in Kenya, Sogo elsewhere."},{"time":557000,"text":"Well, you see self-organizing patterns that spontaneously occur in this board game."},{"time":562000,"text":"And the folks in Ghana knew about these self-organizing patterns"},{"time":565000,"text":"and would use them strategically."},{"time":567000,"text":"So this is very conscious knowledge."}]},{"cues":[{"time":569000,"text":"Here's a wonderful fractal."},{"time":571000,"text":"Anywhere you go in the Sahel, you'll see this windscreen."},{"time":575000,"text":"And of course fences around the world are all Cartesian, all strictly linear."},{"time":579000,"text":"But here in Africa, you've got these nonlinear scaling fences."},{"time":583000,"text":"So I tracked down one of the folks who makes these things,"},{"time":585000,"text":"this guy in Mali just outside of Bamako, and I asked him,"},{"time":589000,"text":"\"How come you're making fractal fences? Because nobody else is.\""},{"time":591000,"text":"And his answer was very interesting."},{"time":593000,"text":"He said, \"Well, if I lived in the jungle, I would only use the long rows of straw"},{"time":598000,"text":"because they're very quick and they're very cheap."},{"time":600000,"text":"It doesn't take much time, doesn't take much straw.\""},{"time":603000,"text":"He said, \"but wind and dust goes through pretty easily."},{"time":605000,"text":"Now, the tight rows up at the very top, they really hold out the wind and dust."},{"time":609000,"text":"But it takes a lot of time, and it takes a lot of straw because they're really tight.\""},{"time":614000,"text":"\"Now,\" he said, \"we know from experience"},{"time":616000,"text":"that the farther up from the ground you go, the stronger the wind blows.\""},{"time":621000,"text":"Right? It's just like a cost-benefit analysis."},{"time":624000,"text":"And I measured out the lengths of straw,"},{"time":626000,"text":"put it on a log-log plot, got the scaling exponent,"},{"time":628000,"text":"and it almost exactly matches the scaling exponent for the relationship between wind speed and height"},{"time":633000,"text":"in the wind engineering handbook."},{"time":634000,"text":"So these guys are right on target for a practical use of scaling technology."}]},{"cues":[{"time":639000,"text":"The most complex example of an algorithmic approach to fractals that I found"},{"time":644000,"text":"was actually not in geometry, it was in a symbolic code,"},{"time":646000,"text":"and this was Bamana sand divination."},{"time":649000,"text":"And the same divination system is found all over Africa."},{"time":652000,"text":"You can find it on the East Coast as well as the West Coast,"},{"time":657000,"text":"and often the symbols are very well preserved,"},{"time":659000,"text":"so each of these symbols has four bits -- it's a four-bit binary word --"},{"time":665000,"text":"you draw these lines in the sand randomly, and then you count off,"},{"time":670000,"text":"and if it's an odd number, you put down one stroke,"},{"time":672000,"text":"and if it's an even number, you put down two strokes."},{"time":674000,"text":"And they did this very rapidly,"},{"time":677000,"text":"and I couldn't understand where they were getting --"},{"time":679000,"text":"they only did the randomness four times --"},{"time":681000,"text":"I couldn't understand where they were getting the other 12 symbols."},{"time":683000,"text":"And they wouldn't tell me."},{"time":685000,"text":"They said, \"No, no, I can't tell you about this.\""},{"time":687000,"text":"And I said, \"Well look, I'll pay you, you can be my teacher,"},{"time":689000,"text":"and I'll come each day and pay you.\""},{"time":691000,"text":"They said, \"It's not a matter of money. This is a religious matter.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":694000,"text":"And finally, out of desperation, I said,"},{"time":695000,"text":"\"Well, let me explain Georg Cantor in 1877.\""},{"time":698000,"text":"And I started explaining why I was there in Africa,"},{"time":702000,"text":"and they got very excited when they saw the Cantor set."},{"time":704000,"text":"And one of them said, \"Come here. I think I can help you out here.\""},{"time":708000,"text":"And so he took me through the initiation ritual for a Bamana priest."},{"time":713000,"text":"And of course, I was only interested in the math,"},{"time":715000,"text":"so the whole time, he kept shaking his head going,"},{"time":717000,"text":"\"You know, I didn't learn it this way.\""},{"time":718000,"text":"But I had to sleep with a kola nut next to my bed, buried in sand,"},{"time":722000,"text":"and give seven coins to seven lepers and so on."},{"time":725000,"text":"And finally, he revealed the truth of the matter."},{"time":730000,"text":"And it turns out it's a pseudo-random number generator using deterministic chaos."},{"time":734000,"text":"When you have a four-bit symbol, you then put it together with another one sideways."},{"time":740000,"text":"So even plus odd gives you odd."},{"time":742000,"text":"Odd plus even gives you odd."},{"time":744000,"text":"Even plus even gives you even. Odd plus odd gives you even."},{"time":747000,"text":"It's addition modulo 2, just like in the parity bit check on your computer."},{"time":751000,"text":"And then you take this symbol, and you put it back in"},{"time":755000,"text":"so it's a self-generating diversity of symbols."},{"time":757000,"text":"They're truly using a kind of deterministic chaos in doing this."},{"time":761000,"text":"Now, because it's a binary code,"},{"time":763000,"text":"you can actually implement this in hardware --"},{"time":765000,"text":"what a fantastic teaching tool that should be in African engineering schools."}]},{"cues":[{"time":770000,"text":"And the most interesting thing I found out about it was historical."},{"time":773000,"text":"In the 12th century, Hugo of Santalla brought it from Islamic mystics into Spain."},{"time":779000,"text":"And there it entered into the alchemy community as geomancy:"},{"time":785000,"text":"divination through the earth."},{"time":787000,"text":"This is a geomantic chart drawn for King Richard II in 1390."},{"time":792000,"text":"Leibniz, the German mathematician,"},{"time":795000,"text":"talked about geomancy in his dissertation called \"De Combinatoria.\""},{"time":799000,"text":"And he said, \"Well, instead of using one stroke and two strokes,"},{"time":803000,"text":"let's use a one and a zero, and we can count by powers of two.\""},{"time":807000,"text":"Right? Ones and zeros, the binary code."},{"time":809000,"text":"George Boole took Leibniz's binary code and created Boolean algebra,"},{"time":812000,"text":"and John von Neumann took Boolean algebra and created the digital computer."},{"time":815000,"text":"So all these little PDAs and laptops --"},{"time":818000,"text":"every digital circuit in the world -- started in Africa."},{"time":821000,"text":"And I know Brian Eno says there's not enough Africa in computers,"},{"time":826000,"text":"but you know, I don't think there's enough African history in Brian Eno."},{"time":831000,"text":"(Laughter) (Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":834000,"text":"So let me end with just a few words about applications that we've found for this."},{"time":838000,"text":"And you can go to our website,"},{"time":840000,"text":"the applets are all free; they just run in the browser."},{"time":842000,"text":"Anybody in the world can use them."},{"time":844000,"text":"The National Science Foundation's Broadening Participation in Computing program"},{"time":849000,"text":"recently awarded us a grant to make a programmable version of these design tools,"},{"time":856000,"text":"so hopefully in three years, anybody'll be able to go on the Web"},{"time":858000,"text":"and create their own simulations and their own artifacts."},{"time":861000,"text":"We've focused in the U.S. on African-American students as well as Native American and Latino."},{"time":866000,"text":"We've found statistically significant improvement with children using this software in a mathematics class"},{"time":872000,"text":"in comparison with a control group that did not have the software."},{"time":875000,"text":"So it's really very successful teaching children that they have a heritage that's about mathematics,"},{"time":881000,"text":"that it's not just about singing and dancing."},{"time":885000,"text":"We've started a pilot program in Ghana."},{"time":888000,"text":"We got a small seed grant, just to see if folks would be willing to work with us on this;"},{"time":893000,"text":"we're very excited about the future possibilities for that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":896000,"text":"We've also been working in design."},{"time":898000,"text":"I didn't put his name up here -- my colleague, Kerry, in Kenya, has come up with this great idea"},{"time":903000,"text":"for using fractal structure for postal address in villages that have fractal structure,"},{"time":908000,"text":"because if you try to impose a grid structure postal system on a fractal village,"},{"time":912000,"text":"it doesn't quite fit."},{"time":914000,"text":"Bernard Tschumi at Columbia University has finished using this in a design for a museum of African art."},{"time":919000,"text":"David Hughes at Ohio State University has written a primer on Afrocentric architecture"},{"time":927000,"text":"in which he's used some of these fractal structures."}]},{"cues":[{"time":929000,"text":"And finally, I just wanted to point out that this idea of self-organization,"},{"time":934000,"text":"as we heard earlier, it's in the brain."},{"time":936000,"text":"It's in the -- it's in Google's search engine."},{"time":941000,"text":"Actually, the reason that Google was such a success"},{"time":943000,"text":"is because they were the first ones to take advantage of the self-organizing properties of the web."},{"time":947000,"text":"It's in ecological sustainability."},{"time":949000,"text":"It's in the developmental power of entrepreneurship,"},{"time":951000,"text":"the ethical power of democracy."},{"time":954000,"text":"It's also in some bad things."},{"time":956000,"text":"Self-organization is why the AIDS virus is spreading so fast."},{"time":959000,"text":"And if you don't think that capitalism, which is self-organizing, can have destructive effects,"},{"time":963000,"text":"you haven't opened your eyes enough."},{"time":965000,"text":"So we need to think about, as was spoken earlier,"},{"time":969000,"text":"the traditional African methods for doing self-organization."},{"time":971000,"text":"These are robust algorithms."},{"time":974000,"text":"These are ways of doing self-organization -- of doing entrepreneurship --"},{"time":977000,"text":"that are gentle, that are egalitarian."},{"time":979000,"text":"So if we want to find a better way of doing that kind of work,"},{"time":983000,"text":"we need look only no farther than Africa to find these robust self-organizing algorithms."},{"time":988000,"text":"Thank you."}]}]}